<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 92 / Bush calls on UN to sanction use of force in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, JUDY DEMPSEY and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush yesterday urged the United Nations to pass a
resolution authorising the use of force, if necessary, to ensure
humanitarian aid reaches war-torn Bosnia.
The US would extend full diplomatic recognition to the former Yugoslav
republic, he added, as well as to Croatia and Slovenia, two other breakaway
Yugoslav states.
Mr Bush was responding to growing international pressure for action to stop
the fighting in Bosnia and to increasing condemnation of Serbia's role in
the Yugoslav conflict.
But he voiced extreme reluctance at the idea of intervention in 'blood
feuds'. He pointedly referred to the use of force only for the purpose of
getting supplies through to civilians, avoiding any suggestion of air
strikes against Serb irregular forces or other military action to end the
ethnic conflict.
Pressure for UN-authorised action has been fuelled by media reports of
alleged atrocities in detention camps in Bosnia and an escalation of
fighting in and around Sarajevo, the republic's besieged capital.
Some British journalists have just been allowed to visit Serb-run detention
camps holding Croats and Moslems. They saw emaciated figures and heard
allegations of violence, which they could not verify.
The European Community condemned what it called 'repulsive and despicable'
Serb camps to detain Bosnian civilians. A statement issued by the British EC
presidency demanded that the Belgrade government press Bosnian Serbs to let
international observers, especially from the Red Cross, into the camps.
Member countries of Nato agreed to draw up contingency plans for possible
use of western military force to make sure humanitarian aid gets through to
Yugoslav republics. The plans will include the possibility of opening up a
land corridor to Sarajevo for armed relief convoys.
In his latest response to the growing crisis, Mr Bush condemned what he
described as 'the vile policy of ethnic cleansing' in Bosnia. He did not
specifically identify Serbia as the prime culprit but added that its
government had to understand it would pay 'a real price' for aggression.
In an article in the New York Times, Lady Thatcher, former British prime
minister, called for military action against Serbia: 'A clear threat of
military action would force Serbia into contemplating an end to its
aggression.'
Mr John Major again ruled out military intervention. 'All the advice I have
tells me that we cannot use force . . . without disproportionate risk to the
lives of civilians and our armed forces,' he told Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal
Democrat leader, who earlier in the week advocated some form of military
initiative in Bosnia.
Islamic nations press UN, Page 2
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
