<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Markets await payroll figure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR traded in tight ranges against the D-Mark yesterday as the
markets anxiously awaited today's US non-farm payroll figure for July,
writes James Blitz.
The payroll figure is widely seen as the big number of the week, with the
market expecting a rise in US employment of anything up to 200,000 on the
month. Dealers believe that if the figure comes through as expected, the
dollar could make a concerted move towards DM1.50. There is also speculation
that June's reported fall of 117,000 in non-farm payroll was greatly
overstated and some think it could be revised all the way up to a 100,000
increase.
However, a leading London economist said there was still deep uncertainty
over the jobless figures: 'We have got uncertain revisions, huge seasonal
adjustments and one-off adjustments for government-sponsored work schemes,
so the market has every right to be paralysed with fear.'
The US currency received a small boost yesterday from the Bundesbank's
decision not to raise its emergency Lombard rate. Adding to the more relaxed
mood was July's figure for German manufacturing orders, which was down 1.8
per cent on the month. Signs that the German economy is weakening will put
pressure on the Bundesbank not to tighten policy further.
However, analysts believe there are still reasons to fear a Lombard rate
rise this autumn. Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief economist at Yamaichi
International, thinks Germany's M3 money supply figure for August, due out
in three weeks time, will show monetary growth peaking at 9.5 per cent. He
believes that the Bundesbank could increase the Lombard rate by  1/4
percentage point in the wake of this.
In London, the dollar ended higher against the D-Mark at DM1.4815 compared
to a previous finish of DM1.4760. At the close of New York trading the US
currency had slipped back to DM1.4772.
After having fallen about 2 pfennigs this week, sterling's descent against
the D-Mark was halted yesterday. The UK currency finished a little firmer at
DM2.8275, after a previous close of DM2.8250.
Dealers, however, remain bearish towards the currency, which is testing its
floor against both the Portuguese escudo and the Spanish peseta in the
European exchange rate mechanism. An analyst sugg-ested that if the pound
drifts down to DM2.80 in forthcoming days, the Bank of England will be
forced to respond with heavy intervention.
The Italian lira showed a mild improvement against the D-Mark, ending at
L756.0 compared to the previous close of L756.5, as did the French franc,
with a finish of FFr3.3770 to the German unit, against FFr3.3800 previously.
</TEXT>
