<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 92 / TV gains access to Scots courts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH courts are to become the first in the UK to admit television
cameras, it was announced yesterday. Lord Hope, the Lord President, who is
head of the Scottish judiciary, yesterday said he was in favour of TV
cameras covering criminal and civil appeal hearings.
The historic decision was welcomed by advocates and solicitors in Scotland,
and by broadcasting organisations. In London, the Bar Council  - the
barristers' ruling body - said the decision should be emulated in England
and Wales.
Lord Hope said the introduction of television cameras would require
'detailed investigation and experiment', and no date could be given for when
it would begin. Scotland has a separate legal system from that of England
and Wales, where a law of 1925 bans photography in court.
Lord Hope said it was likely that court proceedings could be televised
'without undue interference'. Parliament was televised and there was
'sufficient support within the judiciary and the legal profession in
Scotland' for the introduction of TV cameras.
Under Lord Hope's decision, neither criminal nor civil trials may be
televised while they are in progress because of 'risks to the administration
of justice'. But they may be filmed for later broadcast for documentary and
educational purposes, provided all parties agreed and the presiding judge
approved the final product before it was broadcast.
The televising of appeal hearings would be subject to the approval of the
presiding judge.
Ceremonies in courtrooms could be televised and pictures of judges would be
allowed for archive purposes, but without sound.
Lord Hope said it was in the public interest that people should know how
justice was administered.
TV cameras are allowed in criminal trials in the US.
In 1989, the English Bar Council recommended that pilot projects of
televising courts be introduced and sponsored a private member's bill that
would have amended the law accordingly.
</TEXT>
