FT  06 AUG 92 / International Company News: Brascan holds dividend in spite
of slight decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRASCAN, a key holding company in the business empire controlled by
Toronto's Bronfman family, has reported slightly lower second-quarter
earnings but maintained its quarterly dividend.
A greatly improved performance by natural resource subsidiaries and lower
interest charges were offset by a smaller contribution from financial
services and investments. Second-quarter earnings dipped to CDollars 8.3m
(Dollars 7m) from CDollars 9.8m.
Earnings per share rose to 2 cents from 1 cent, reflecting lower preferred
share dividend payments. Brascan's share of group revenues climbed to
CDollars 2.63bn from CDollars 2.42bn.
The company, whose interests include controlling stakes in Noranda, the
mining and forestry group and Royal Trust, a large Canadian financial
institution, said its performance should improve as the business recovery
gathers momentum.
Some companies under its wing have recently cut dividends, but Brascan
maintained its own quarterly payout at 26 cents a share.
