<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Courts urged to speed up recovery of bad debts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS AIMED at halving the time courts take to deal with bad debt cases are
to be presented to the government next week by the Confederation of British
Industry.
The proposals would mean the establishment of special debt recovery
tribunals under the aegis of the High Court. County courts would be
bypassed, except for the very smallest claims.
The CBI is highly critical of the time taken to process bad debt cases -
undefended cases take about 60 days in the High Court and 114 days in the
county court.
These figures could be cut to about 38 days, the CBI says. For defended
cases, the time taken could be cut to 66 days from 100 days in the High
Court and 128 in the county court. A CBI survey last year found that nearly
60 per cent of small businesses were finding late payment of bills and bad
debts a significant hindrance. Nearly 20 per cent said they were at risk of
failing because of the problem.
Court procedures for recovery of debts are so cumbersome that some
businesses are deliberately delaying payment, says the CBI, and 'feeling
they can get away with it'. Payments to one in five businesses regularly
exceed 75 days according to the CBI research.
The latest proposals for speeding court procedures are due to be submitted
by the CBI's smaller firms council to the lord chancellor's department and
to Baroness Denton, small firms minister, early next week.
The plans have been drawn up in conjunction with Davies Arnold Cooper, the
City firm of solicitors.
The CBI is also proposing the greater use of incentives for court officials
to recover debts. Mr Richard Brucciani, CBI smaller firms council chairman,
said yesterday that, under the present system, High Court sheriffs who were
paid according to results 'are far more effective than county court bailiffs
who are paid a fixed salary'.
A Pounds 500 ceiling for county court bad debt claims should be set, says
the CBI, with larger claims pushed into the High Court 'where better results
can be achieved'. It should also be possible to start legal action without
first sending a solicitor's letter, argues the CBI.
</TEXT>
