<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Fall in job-related training admitted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROPORTION of workers receiving job-related training has declined
noticeably during the recession, a Department of Employment analysis
acknowledged yesterday.
The report in the department's Employment Gazette also suggests that many of
the participants in the government's Employment Training and Youth Training
schemes do not believe they are receiving significant amounts of job-related
training.
The analysis, which draws on statistics published earlier this year in the
annual Labour Force Survey, will heighten fears that skill shortages will
emerge as a restraint on economic growth once the present recession ends.
Although this happened in the previous recession in the early 1980s, the
government had hoped that companies would heed its calls to maintain
training budgets at their pre-recession levels.
The Employment Gazette report shows that 14.9 per cent, or 3.16m employees,
of working age in Britain reported receiving training related to their jobs
in the four weeks before the Labour Force Survey in the spring of last year.
Although this represents a significant increase on figures in the early
1980s - it compares with 9.2 per cent in 1984 - it is down on the 15.4 per
cent of 1990.
The likelihood is that the proportion will have decreased considerably
further since the spring of last year because the recession has continued
for longer than many analysts and employers expected.
The gazette's report also charts a decline in apprenticeships. On the basis
of responses to the survey it is estimated that 330,000 people in Britain
were doing an apprenticeship last year, against 367,000 in 1989, when they
were at their peak following the recession of the early 1980s.
An encouraging statistic for the government is that training programmes such
as YT, ET and apprenticeships account for only about 10 per cent of training
activity recorded by the survey.
This indicates that the other 90 per cent of people who said they had
received job-related training in the four weeks before the survey were
getting it on a continuing basis as part of their employment.
However, the analysis notes that nearly 200,000 of the 738,000 people who
said they were participating in YT, ET or trade apprenticeship did not feel
they had undertaken any job-related training in the four weeks before the
survey.
This will fuel fears about the effectiveness of some of the training
schemes.
The analysis says there are no obvious reasons for the responses, although
'variations in individuals' perception of what constitutes job-related
training is a possible explanation.
'For example, some may not consider work experience or on-the-job learning
as being related to training.'
The analysis also notes that off-the-job training was the most common format
and the incidence of training generally declined with age.
Employment Gazette, August 1992. HMSO. Pounds 4.50 a copy or Pounds 48
annual subscription.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
