<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / National Savings rates cut: Mortgage lenders say move eases
pressure to raise cost of borrowing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD, PHILIP COGGAN, PETER NORMAN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT cut National Savings interest rates yesterday in a move
apparently aimed at avoiding mortgage rate rises by building societies. This
was the second rate cut by National Savings in just over two weeks.
The reduction comes at the end of a week of repeated warnings by the Council
of Mortgage Lenders and building society executives that they would soon be
forced to put up mortgage interest rates because of competition from
National Savings.
National Savings rates have been cut on a variety of products by between
0.25 and 0.8 percentage points. The 37th issue of tax-free certificates,
introduced only in May, has been withdrawn. The new 38th issue will pay 7.5
per cent if held for five years, against 8 per cent on the 37th issue.
Mortgage lenders welcomed the news, saying it removed the likelihood of an
immediate rates rise.
Halifax, the largest UK mortgage lender, which earlier in the day called for
the stamp duty threshold to be doubled to Pounds 60,000 to help the housing
market, said the National Savings decision eased some of the competitive
pressures on interest rates but added: 'We will still need to watch the
situation closely.'
Nationwide, the second-largest society, said it might be able to make a
small reduction in its savings rates.
Yesterday's cuts followed a sharp increase in the contribution of National
Savings' products to funding the public sector borrowing requirement in
recent months. National Savings estimated that it contributed Pounds 600m to
funding the PSBR last month, lifting its total contribution to financing the
government deficit to Pounds 2.1bn in the first four months of the financial
year.
The government's official PSBR target for 1992-93 is Pounds 28bn, but the
outturn is expected to be several billion pounds higher.
Treasury officials said this inflow was well ahead of the share of funding
allocated to National Savings. Explaining yesterday's cuts, Mr Anthony
Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury, said the government did 'not
wish to see National Savings interest rates kept any higher than is
necessary to make their contribution to funding'.
Treasury officials denied that this third cut in National Savings rates
since the election was a direct result of pressure from the building
societies to make National Savings rates less attractive. But they admitted
that ministers had taken into account the effect of the high level of
inflows into National Savings on building society finances.
The officials added that the decision had no implications for UK bank base
rates, which have been at 10 per cent since May 5. Base rates would be kept
at whatever level was necessary to maintain sterling's position in the
European exchange rate mechanism and to continue to bear down on inflation,
they said.
City economists said the cuts showed that last month's half-point reduction
in the First Option Bond rate had failed to bolster building society
inflows.
Mr Kevin Gardiner, UK economist at SG Warburg Securities, said the cuts, so
soon after the July measure, gave the impression the government was
panicking in its desire to avoid higher mortgage rates. It was unclear that
the latest move would be sufficient 'to do the trick'.
The move was welcomed by senior Tory backbenchers, some of whom have been
critical of the government's economic policy in recent weeks. Mr Terence
Higgins, former chairman of the all-party Treasury and Civil Service
committee, said it was 'entirely sensible' for the government to adopt a
'flexible attitude' in current circumstances.
Mr Nick Brown, Labour's frontbench Treasury spokesman, described the move as
'a very small adjustment' which was 'unlikely to meet the needs of the
present situation'.
National Savings cut will help societies, Page 7
Construction on frail foundations, Page 15
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
