<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / International Capital Markets: Japan's CP market set to
resume growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S domestic commercial paper (CP) market will grow again, but credit
risks will rise, Moody's Investors Service said in a study released this
week, Reuter reports from Tokyo.
Growth will resume because of more liberal market regulations, Japanese
corporations' increased use of domestic CP for working capital purposes and
of Japanese banks' reduced ability to offer either competitive short-term
lending rates or CP investor protection, the study said.
Yen CP outstandings grew to a peak of Y15,800bn (Dollars 124.16bn) in 1990,
falling to Y9,400bn in June 1991, and was about Y9,700bn in March 1992.
Until 1991, about 90 per cent of yen commercial paper was issued for
financial arbitrage, where issuers ploughed the funds back into
higher-yielding investments. Such arbitrage has become more difficult,
causing volume to taper off, Moody's said.
</TEXT>
