<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Wallace Smith Trust Collapse: Global labyrinth is explored -
The long and twisting path of the merchant bank's connections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, ANDREW JACK and BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMPLEX network of companies and family trusts centred in Canada and the
UK has been uncovered as attempts are made to trace more than Pounds 100m of
missing assets from the collapsed Wallace Smith merchant bank.
KPMG Peat Marwick, the liquidator, which is suing the Royal Bank of Scotland
and National Westminster Bank, is still trying to determine the extent of
connections between Wallace Smith Holdings, the Canadian-registered company
that received the transfers, and Wallace Smith Trust Company, to which the
payments should allegedly have gone.
Mr Nick Press, a US consultant who has been acting as chief operating
officer of the Canadian-based Wallace Smith Group since June 1991, said that
the Wallace Smith Canadian interests were organised in a complicated series
of interlocked family trusts.
He said he was brought in by one of the group directors to be 'a guardian of
the gate' and that he was defending the Canadian company against litigation
and making claims of its own against others.
Wallace Smith Holdings, the subsidiary which received the disputed cash, is
now Dundalk Investment Company, a subsidiary of Colchester Trust, which is
in turn linked with other Wallace Smith trusts registered in Canada.
The Wallace Smith Group is the parent of a string of subsidiaries, now
mostly in liquidation, in the UK, US, Caribbean, Spain and Italy. The most
important of these subsidiaries appears to have been the Wallace Smith Trust
Company, which specialised in money market operations from its base in
Winchester House, London Wall, in the City of London. The trust was closed
last year amid allegations of fraud.
Dundalk is listed as a creditor in the most recent published accounts of
Herongrove and British Trusts Association, both UK subsidiaries of the
Wallace Smith Group.
The elusive nature of the relationship between the companies is shown in the
auditors' reports in the accounts of several of the Wallace Smith Group's UK
subsidiaries, which draw attention to 'professional advisory services to
corporations controlled by a board of independent trustees of which a
director was a minority trustee and a non-executive director'.
The 1990 accounts for Wallace Smith Trust Group show that one of the
directors within the group was paid more than Pounds 180,000 during the
year, and a further five more than Pounds 90,000.
Mr Smith, who is living in London and awaiting a court appearance on charges
relating to a Serious Fraud Office investigation, was described by former
employees as a quiet man. One former colleague said he had come from a
family with Lithuanian origins which settled in the Alberta area of Canada.
A former banker who had dealings with him said: 'When he was going to speak
he would pause. He takes a long time to say anything.'
Mr Smith spent much of his early career with Nesbitt Thomson, a Canadian
broking company. He pioneered a UK arm of the company before breaking away
in the early 1970s to set up another Canadian based company called McDunn
Silcox.
In recent years the group's most active companies in Canada were Wallace
Smith Securities and Wallace Smith &amp; Co. The former specialised in trading
Canadian securities. Most of the business of Wallace Smith &amp; Co was in the
US, largely in the Euro-Canadian and foreign currency markets.
Mr Press said that none of the Wallace Smith companies in Canada was
actively trading. He said that business dried up last summer after the UK
liquidation.
According to Mr Press the UK liquidators petitioned a UK court a year ago to
wind up two of the key Canadian companies, Wallace Smith Group and Wallace
Smith &amp; Co. The petition was dismissed earlier this year.
Mr Press said the Canadian group was suing Peat Marwick for between Pounds
5m and Pounds 7m, mainly for 'interruption of business'.
In addition, Wallace Smith &amp; Co has a creditor claim of Pounds 1.2m against
Wallace Smith Trust Group in the UK.
Mr Smith's involvement as chairman of Wallace Smith Group Ltd in Canada, and
director of some of the other companies, was severed the day after the
British fraud authorities entered the company in April 1991.
Garstangs, Mr Smith's Bolton-based solicitor, rejected suggestions in
yesterday's Financial Times that its client enjoyed a wealthy lifestyle.
The firm said last night that Mr Smith had made a successful application for
legal aid to defend the criminal proceedings against him and denied that he
had owned property in Chelsea and the Bahamas.
Garstangs added that Mr Smith denied any dishonesty or fraudulent trading
and was strenuously defending the proceedings against him.
</TEXT>
