<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / GLC spectre continues to haunt Tories: The rumpus over
London's County Hall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN the then Mrs Margaret Thatcher abolished the Greater London Council in
1986 - exasperated by Mr Ken Livingstone's use of it as a soapbox for the
Labour left just across the Thames from the Houses of Parliament - she
thought she had neutered County Hall once and for all.
Six years later, however, the building is causing ministers as much
embarrassment as did Mr Livingstone in his heyday.
The current rumpus, which could soon reach the courts, is of the
government's making. Put bluntly, it has been unable to make up its mind
about the future of the building.
Five months ago it agreed that the London Residuary Body, the quango set up
to dispose of the GLC's assets, could sell County Hall to the Japanese
Shirayama group. The contract included an 'opt-out' clause operable until
November.
Everyone, not least the residuary body and Shirayama, assumed that the
clause was an escape route for the Labour party if it won the general
election. And a Labour victory appeared to be the only hope for the
year-long campaign by the London School of Economics to move from Aldwych to
the grander and more spacious South Bank site.
The Conservatives won the general election. But Mr Michael Howard replaced
Mr Michael Heseltine as environment secretary and Mrs Gillian Shephard, a
strong supporter of the LSE, was one of the new faces at the cabinet table.
Mr John Ashworth, the LSE's ebullient director, also had a route to the
prime minister through well-placed advocates in the No 10 policy unit.
The LSE went into top lobbying gear with its vision of being 'the European
social science university' and achieved a coup last week when Mr Howard let
it submit a bid.
Mr Howard's action, taken after months of speculation, understandably
infuriated Shirayama, which had believed that only the Labour party stood in
the way of its long-cherished plans for a luxury hotel beside the Thames.
It also enraged Sir Godfrey Taylor, chairman of the London Residuary Body,
who felt he had been led up and down the garden path by a dithering
government.
This, plus irritation at the intensity of Mr Ashworth's lobbying and the
belief that the Shirayama deal represented better financial value for the
London boroughs, led to the residuary body yesterday issuing 'advice' in
scathing terms about the LSE's bid, 'strongly urging' Mr Howard to reject it
and to delete the opt-out clause.
Having got so far, the LSE has problems of its own. With a tight public
spending round ahead and university funding particularly constrained, it was
made clear to Mr Ashworth that no handouts were on offer. The LSE had to
produce a realistic bid.
Accordingly, the Pounds 20m bid for the entire site offered by the
university in March jointly with Advanta, a German property developer, has
been increased to Pounds 65m - less than Shirayama's Pounds 60m offer for
the riverside building alone.
There are doubts about the LSE's ability to foot the bill. It is not just
the direct financial side - in particular the optimistic assumption that its
existing site in central London will net Pounds 100m by 1995. The bid also
assumes that the LSE can double its postgraduate numbers within four years -
which means finding another 2,500 fee-paying, high-calibre social science
students, and the staff to supervise them.
One LSE governor said: 'If this were France or Germany they'd be giving us
the building free for prestige.'
The French and Germans, of course, would not have abolished the elected
governments of Paris or Berlin in the first place.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                    BATTLE FOR THE COUNTY HALL SITE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
1986 Abolition of Greater London Council; London Residuary Body
established; Inner London Education Authority remains in County Hall
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
April 1990 Abolition of education authority
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Oct 1990 Collapse of LRB's contract with County Hall Development Group
for mixed hotel, residential and office use
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Sept 1991 Michael Heseltine grants planning permission for mixed use
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
March 1992 LRB sells County Hall to Shirayama for pounds 60m with
Heseltine's consent (opt-out clause allows government to withdraw from
deal until end of November) and rejects pounds 20m bid form London
School of Economics and Advanta for County Hall and surrounding sites
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
April 1992 Michael Howard replaces Heseltine as environment secretary
after general election
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
July 1992 Howard takes sale of County Hall out of LRB's hands; LSE bids
pounds 65m for hall and surrounding sites
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Aug 1992 LRB 'strongly urges' Howard to reject LSE bid
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
