<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Questions on Belling pension fund money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO directors at Belling, the cooker manufacturer which went into
receivership in May, have come under scrutiny for their actions in relation
to the company's pension fund.
The Law Debenture Trust, which was appointed by Belling's receivers to act
as independent trustees to the pension fund, is considering legal action
over investments made by the scheme and a Pounds 2.1m shortfall in the fund.
In December last year, just five months before the company went into
receivership, the pension fund paid Pounds 5.5m to buy Compound Sections, a
Belling subsidiary. The pension fund was controlled by two Belling directors
at the time. The Law Debenture Trust is questioning whether this was an
appropriate investment. The trust has also taken advice on action to recover
Pounds 2.1m borrowed from the fund. The trust is considering suits against
several possible defendants, including Mr CJ Deacon, a solicitor in
Newcastle-under-Lyme, Stafford-shire. It is understood he undertook to hold
the Pounds 2.1m pending a Dollars 50m loan to Belling.
The loan was arranged last summer through Global Prospect Funding, a client
of Mr Deacon. Belling agreed to pay a year's interest, equivalent to Pounds
2.1m, before receiving the capital. Belling borrowed the money from the
fund.
In April an Isle of Man registered company, Finchley Investments, provided
security for the interest payment when the loan was not forthcoming. The
security was a CDollars 1.75m stake in the Vancouver natural resources
company, Western &amp; Pacific. The shares are now estimated to be worth a
fraction of that. Mr Deacon said he was unaware the trust was considering
action. He said the money would be repaid 'literally any time'. He denied he
signed a receipt on receiving the Pounds 2.1m, promising to hold the money
until Global paid the cash. According to an agreement in April, he said,
repayment was not yet due.
</TEXT>
