<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / BMA critical of fees for health advisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE British Medical Association yesterday strongly criticised the government
for employing expert advisers on nutrition and health who accepted payments
from food and pharmaceutical manufacturers.
The BMA said the practice undermined public confidence in the quality of
government advice.
The association was responding to the disclosure by the Department of Health
that many of its 43 outside advisers on food and health had received
personal payments from food and pharmaceutical manufacturers or were
responsible for research projects funded by these companies.
Dr Fleur Fisher, head of the BMA's professional and scientific division,
said: 'The mildest thing one can say is that it looks extraordinarily
ill-advised to involve people with links with these industries. It
undermines the credibility of the experts' reports in people's minds.'
Mr Derek Jackson, director of the Coronary Prevention Group, said experts
should be banned from sitting on government advisory committees if they
received income from any organisation with a vested interest in the results
of the committees' work.
The BMA and the Coronary Prevention Group particularly criticised advisers
who received personal payments from industry. Dr Fisher said industrial
funding of research was unavoidable, while Mr Jackson said such funding
should be accepted only if the research was not intended to serve the
interests of individual companies.
Most of the department's advisers are qualified doctors and academics.
Thirteen of them declared receiving personal payments from food and
pharmaceutical companies for consultancy and other services, while 15 said
they were responsible for research or training projects funded by these
industries. Several advisers declared both types of commercial interest.
Only 19 said they had none.
The advisers sit on the committee on medical aspects of food policy (Coma),
the department's main expert body, and on panels dealing with issues
including cardiovascular work, diets of the elderly, child nutrition and
novel foods.
According to the register of commercial interests published by the
department, one member of its working group on the weaning diet, Mr RA
Hendey, is a full-time employee of Nestle, the world's largest producer of
baby foods. Dr Fisher expressed astonishment that he should be employed as a
government adviser.
The register shows that Dr Roger Whitehead, who chaired a landmark report on
diet and nutrition published by the department last year, is a member of the
council of the Nestle Foundation. Dr Whitehead, director of the Dunn
clinical research centre in Cambridge, is also a paid adviser to the Milk
Marketing Board.
The register does not give the value of payments. Professor David Hull of
Nottingham University Medical Hospital, who received money from Nutricia, a
Dutch food group, said the exact amounts were not of legitimate public
interest.
The department said it required all advisers to register their commercial
interests when appointed and to abstain from discussions on topics in which
they had a personal financial interest. It saw no need for any changes in
the rules.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, said publication of the register
marked an advance in open government. However, several advisers said the
information contained in the register was collected more than a year ago.
The department could not explain why the register had not been disclosed
until now.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
