<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Brewers increase wholesale beer prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BEER prices in most pubs are expected to rise by between 4p and 6p a pint
after increases in wholesale prices by the national brewers. Prices of some
premium beers in pubs in the south-east may be up to 10p a pint higher.
The brewers, which were strongly criticised last year after beer prices, net
of duty, rose 11 per cent, have limited the rise in wholesale prices to
about the level of inflation in the past three months.
Allied-Lyons has raised wholesale prices by 3 per cent, less than the
inflation rate of 3.9 per cent in the year to June. Prices in its managed
pubs will be 4p to 5p higher in the north of England and 6p to 10p up in the
south - an average increase of 4.5 per cent.
Bass, the country's leading brewer, has lifted wholesale prices in its
northern trading area by Pounds 7.50 a barrel for standard ales and lagers
and Pounds 10 a barrel for premium-brand products - an average increase of
4.4 per cent.
Bass Taverns, the group's managed estate, said retail prices had gone up by
between 4p and 6p. 'This includes the 2p a pint higher duty imposed in the
March Budget, and is the first increase for between 12 and 15 months,' the
company said. 'We are doing everything we can to control costs and price our
beer as competitively as possible.' Whitbread's wholesale prices went up 3.8
per cent in May, the equivalent of about 2p a pint.
Courage increased prices of some leading brands - Fosters, Courage Best and
John Smith's - by 4 per cent but has held the prices of Holsten Pils and
some other brands at last year's levels. Prices in Grand Metropolitan's
managed estate, which Courage supplies, have risen by between 4p and 6p a
pint.
The brewers say the increases are necessary to meet higher production and
distribution costs and to improve retailing margins hit by the recession.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
