<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Gould defiant on Maastricht ratification
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BRYAN GOULD, the defeated challenger for the Labour leadership, has given
a clear signal that the party may face formidable internal dissent over
ratification of the Maastricht treaty.
Yesterday he confirmed that he would oppose the accord in the shadow
cabinet. As a senior member of Mr John Smith's frontbench team, this will
make him a rallying point for Labour's Eurosceptics and the growing number
of pro-Europeans who argue that the party should not squander an opportunity
to defeat the government.
Mr Smith wants Labour to oppose a guillotine motion that would cut short
debate on the treaty when the Maastricht bill returns to the Commons in the
coming session.
But as a lifelong pro-European he is against outright opposition to the
treaty. He is determined that Labour must not be seen to block closer EC
union for the short-term tactical gain of a government defeat.
A measure of Mr Smith's difficulty is that earlier this year more than 50
backbench Labour MPs defied party managers and opposed a second reading of
the Maastricht bill.
Mr Gould argues that one consequence of the Danish referendum which rejected
the Maastricht terms is that Labour is free to adjust its pre-election
stance that grudgingly endorsed the treaty.
During his leadership campaign Mr Gould argued that the treaty did not do
enough to enforce greater democratic accountability in EC institutions and
that its criteria for economic convergence - required to complete economic
and monetary union - failed to address the need for growth and full
employment.
This week Mr Gould hinted that Labour's recent calls for 'co-ordinated
action' across Europe to reduce interest rates appeared to be 'shorthand or
code' endorsing a general devaluation against the D-Mark.
With the leadership's position not finalised, Mr Gould has made clear that
he does not feel bound by collective responsibility. 'It would be disastrous
to go into self-imposed purdah,' he said, adding that he thought it highly
unlikely that he would be unable to accept the final position adopted by the
shadow cabinet.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
