</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A REVIEW of Conservative party internal organisation is thought to have
concluded that a new board of directors should be set up to improve the
party's effectiveness.
Those sitting on the board would be drawn from the various branches of the
party, including constituencies, area offices and the national union, the
party's voluntary arm.
The review - commissioned by Sir Norman Fowler, the party chairman - is
believed to have concluded the board would improve the cohesiveness with
which the party performs activities.
