<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Minister halts Pounds 500m development plans for Kent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has rejected plans for a Pounds 500m package of commercial
and residential developments in an unemployment blackspot in north-east
Kent.
Citibank, the large US bank, and Touche Ross, the accountancy firm - the
promoters of the development - had estimated that the scheme would have
generated about 9,000 jobs on and around the Isle of Sheppey.
The region, for which Swale Borough Council is seeking assisted area status,
has an unemployment rate of more than 12 per cent. This compares with a
national average of 9.6 per cent and a south-east England average of 9.2 per
cent.
The development plan included provision for a privately financed road tunnel
linking Sheppey to the mainland, the expansion of Sheerness Dock and the
construction of 3,300 homes and more than 1m sq metres of industrial and
business space.
Plans for the tunnel were welcomed in 1989 by the Department of Transport,
which said it would be bringing forward road improvements in anticipation of
the tunnel's development.
Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, rejecting four separate planning
applications, said that he recognised the economic problems of the island
but these had to be balanced against other factors.
According to Mr Howard the plans would have harmed a broad range of nature
conservation interests and would have meant the loss of an internationally
important feeding area for migrating birds.
The scale of the developments also exceeded those proposed in the area
structure plan and would have led to a significant increase in traffic
congestion.
Citibank is estimated to have spent more than Pounds 1m financing the
planning applications after Lionhope, the developer which is part of the
Tudor Grange group of companies, went into administrative receivership in
1989.
Touche Ross, the receiver to Lionhope, said yesterday: 'Without the second
crossing of the Swale, to be paid for by Lionhope, the future development of
Sheppey will suffer. In view of the high unemployment in the area it is
particularly unfortunate. We must now carefully review our options.'
Officials at Swale Borough Council, which covers Sheppey, Sittingbourne and
Faversham, said yesterday that the government had failed to recognise the
serious economic problems in the region.
The four sites where developments were proposed were: Ridham on the south
bank of the Swale, where the existing port was to be expanded and 220
hectares of industrial, business and warehouse space developed.
Lappel Bank, where 100 hectares of land was to be reclaimed for the
expansion of Sheerness Dock.
Queenborough, where 300 homes were to be built alongside a marina.
Minster, where 3,000 homes were planned along with schools, medical
facilities, a golf course and some parkland.
The government's rejection of the plans coincided with last week's decision
by the European Commission to drop legal objections to five UK building
projects, including the M3 motorway extension at Twyford Down, Hampshire.
The EC had opposed the schemes on the grounds that environmental impact
studies had not been carried out.
The Nature Conservancy Council had claimed that an environmental impact
study had not been carried out for the Queenborough development proposals on
Sheppey.
</TEXT>
