<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Council may have to shed 1,000 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS OF North Tyneside council met union representatives yesterday to
discuss a proposed restructuring which may cost up to 1,000 jobs, or 10 per
cent of the workforce.
The Labour-controlled authority, which has exhausted its reserves, faces a
deficit of between Pounds 12m and Pounds 20m next year. The reorganisation
is intended to sweep away the departmental structure in favour of service
areas and has been triggered by financial problems.
The authority, which was rate capped in 1985-86 and charge capped in
1990-91, has already made cuts of Pounds 12m this year. It blames its
difficulties on the government's standard spending assessment which, it
says, fails to take account of the level of social deprivation in the
borough. However, Conservative councillors say central government is not to
blame for the problems.
The council has relied on drawing on reserves, and reducing employment to
balance its books for several years. But with an estimated standard spending
assessment of Pounds 134.5m for 1993-94 against projected expenditure of
Pounds 154m, it is having to overhaul its entire structure. The plan will be
finalised in the autumn and implemented once the level of assessment is
known in November.
The authority said yesterday that it was too early to say how many jobs
would go, and what cuts in services would be made. It said, however, that a
10 per cent reduction would be the 'worst case'. An enhanced voluntary
severance scheme, used by the authority in 1990-91 when 600 jobs were cut,
was ruled unlawful by the High Court last year.
Unions, which represent the majority of employees, are sympathetic but have
not ruled out industrial action against compulsory redundancies. Mr Trevor
Johnston, secretary of Nalgo, the local government union, said: 'The council
have a duty to provide employment as well as to service the area.'
</TEXT>
