<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 92 / Reinsurance losses spark legal action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LEADING European reinsurer is taking legal action in an effort to recover
losses of more than Pounds 200m sustained in the London reinsurance market.
Amsterdam-based Nederlandse Reassurantie Groep has started the action after
running up heavy losses at its Victory subsidiary.
The group says that its advisers failed to inform it about the extent of
Victory's exposure to lossmaking spiral reinsurance business - in which
Lloyd's syndicates and companies reinsure each other's exposure to
high-level catastrophe loss - when it bought Victory from Legal &amp; General in
1990.
Solicitors Allison &amp; Humphreys last week served writs against Bacon &amp;
Woodrow, the actuaries, accountants Ernst &amp; Young and Swiss Bank
Corporation. NRG alleges breach of contract and negligence against all three
advisers.
Mr Willem Dikland, NRG chairman, said the group had decided to take action
after carefully reviewing the situation. He said the shortfall in reserves
on Victory's marine and aviation reinsurance accounts amounted to Dollars
480m. The claim does not, however, specify any particular amount of damages.
Bacon &amp; Woodrow said it would vigorously resist the action when NRG first
announced the possible action in June. Swiss Bank Corporation said it had
not been asked to advise on the extent of Victory's reserves.
</TEXT>
