<DATE>920805
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / International Company News: Dresdner Bank improves 20% in
first six months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, HAMBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DRESDNER Bank yesterday became the second of Germany's big three banks to
report robust profits for the first six months of the year.
Buoyed by strong lending demand and increased fee income, Dresdner's partial
operating profits - excluding gains from own account securities trading -
rose by 20 per cent to DM1.29bn (Dollars 869m) better than the market was
expecting.
This follows a 14.7 per cent rise in Commerzbank's partial operating
profits, announced last week, and comes ahead of today's figures from
Deutsche Bank, Germany's biggest bank.
All leading German banks reported double-digit profits growth in the first
four months of the year, and the figures from Dresdner and Commerzbank
suggest that banking remains, with construction, one of only two sectors in
Germany able to defy the recession and deliver strong profits growth.
However, Deutsche's share price has fallen over the past week on worries
that half-year profits will be flat, signalling the end of a long period of
powerful profits growth.
Commenting on the likely outcome for the full year yesterday, Mr Wolfgang
Roller, Dresdner's chief executive, said that profits were likely to show
double-digit growth over 1992 as a whole. He declined to comment on the
possibility that the dividend would be raised this year.
Earnings on interest in the Dresdner group rose by 12.6 per cent to
DM2.95bn, whilst commission income climbed 14.8 per cent to DM1.13bn.
Operating expenses rose by 10.3 per cent, lower than the increase last year,
reflecting what the bank called 'a return to a more normal trend' following
the pronounced increases in the past two years due to the bank's expansion
in east Germany.
Total operating profits - which include the contribution from own account
trading - rose by 15 per cent to DM1.4bn. Dresdner's shares rose DM7 to
close at DM332 yesterday.
Mr Roller, dismissed talk of a power-struggle between Deutsche Bank, on the
one hand, and Dresdner and Allianz, the big insurance company which owns
22.3 per cent of Dresdner, on the other.
Speculation of such a struggle has been fanned in recent days following the
sharp fall in the Allianz share price - and in the German stock market as a
whole - after it published poor figures for 1991 on Tuesday last week. The
shares fell further on Thursday and Friday, triggered by a sell
recommendation from DB Research, the Deutsche Bank research arm.
Mr Roller said that the sell note had caught the stock market at a delicate
moment. Questions about the motivation for the earnings estimate should be
put to DB Research itself, he said. However, he pointed out that Dresdner's
own equity analysts had downgraded their forecasts for Allianz's earnings as
long ago as December last year.
Deutsche, which last month took a significant step into the German insurance
market with the purchase of a 30 per cent stake in Gerling, the largest
privately-owned insurance company in Germany, has argued that the sell
recommendation was based on a fundamental assessment of Allianz's profits
and was not an attempt to knock a rival's share price. Allianz has, for its
part, denied rumours that it has dumped shares in Deutsche Bank by way of
retaliation.
DRESDNER Bank wants to relieve the former Soviet Union's debt problems by
partially accepting repayments in roubles, Reuter reports from Hamburg.
Mr Wolfgang Roeller, the bank's management board chairman, told a press
conference that international banks should grant the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) a partial delay on payment of interest on its
loans.
He added: 'We are prepared to accept a proportion of the interest payments
in roubles.' One condition of accepting roubles was that banks should be
able to use them to buy stakes in companies and property in the former
Soviet Union, he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
