FT  05 AUG 92 / UK Company News: Hartwell cash bid values Trimoco at Pounds
25.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HARTWELL is making a mandatory cash offer for Trimoco following the
conversion of its holding of 11.5 per cent convertible unsecured loan stock.
Its offer of 17.5p per share and Pounds 175 per Pounds 100 nominal of the
outstanding culs values Trimoco, the Dunstable-based motor dealer, at Pounds
25.9m. The announcement was made after the close of the market on which
Trimoco's shares had closed unchanged at 17 1/2 p.
Hartwell, a motor trader ultimately owned by a discretionary trust set up by
Mr Abdul Jameel, believes Trimoco's prospects would be enhanced if it won
control.
Before yesterday Hartwell, and persons acting in concert with it, held a
share stake of 29.8 per cent and 92.1 per cent of the culs.
The conversion into shares raised the holding to 39.4 per cent of the
enlarged capital requiring a bid to be made under the takeover code at a
price set by the code.
The Jameel activities have been raising their holding in Trimoco over the
last year. In December last year Mr John Wei, Hartwell chief executive and
Mr Mahmoud Abdulla, a senior Hartwell executive joined the Trimoco board,
which said at the time that it intended to work closely with the Jameel
organisation on future development.
