<DATE>920805
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / NatWest profits recover sharply: Second-biggest UK clearer
rises 109% despite record losses on lending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster Bank's profits recovered sharply in the first half of
the year, even though its losses on UK lending remained at record levels.
The second-biggest UK clearing bank, as measured by the value of its assets,
also said it expected staff numbers to reduce by 5,000 this year and a
similar number next year.
The departures of two senior executives were announced yesterday. Sir
Geoffrey Littler, chairman of NatWest's merchant bank, County NatWest, and
Mr John Drury, County's chief executive, are leaving.
Lord Alexander, NatWest's chairman, said that Sir Geoffrey and Mr Drury
'decided that there would be no long-term role for them'.
NatWest's pre-tax profits in the six months to June 30 increased 109 per
cent to Pounds 211m, which was also Pounds 101m more than it made in the
whole of last year.
Its bad debt charge fell from Pounds 902m to Pounds 864m. However, within
this total charge, the loan losses suffered by the UK high street banking
business increased from Pounds 556m to Pounds 638m.
Lord Alexander blamed these losses on the bank's relatively high exposure to
the small business lending market - where it has a market share of almost a
third - and also on the bank's disproportionate presence in the south-east
of England, the region hit hardest by the recession.
NatWest has around Pounds 11bn of loans to small businesses and in the past
couple of years has set aside about Pounds 1bn as provisions against losses
on these loans. However, Mr Derek Wanless, the newly appointed chief
executive, said that the bank had no plans to reduce its share of this
market though it has been striving to charge small business customers more.
Last year, NatWest increased the margin on small business lending - the
difference between the lending rate and NatWest's funding rate - by 0.5 per
cent and this margin has widened slightly since then.
NatWest pushed up profits before loan losses from Pounds 984m to Pounds
1.092bn. It bucked the trend set by rivals Lloyds and Midland, which
announced results last week, by increasing non-interest income or earnings
from bankings commissions and fees and from sales of insurance products.
These non-interest earnings rose 12 per cent. Much of the rise came from an
increase in the tariffs paid by customers and also from an improvement in
the rate of collecting these tariffs, thanks to the installation of a
computer system which made it easier to monitor when charges are payable. On
the other hand, interest income fell slightly for two reasons:
The volume of interest-earning loans held by NatWest has fallen;
There has been a rise in the value of loans classified as non-performing.
Operating costs barely changed at Pounds 2.11bn. Within these costs,
personnel expenses fell marginally. Since December, staff numbers have
fallen by 3,100, in spite of the creation of 1,100 new jobs. Excluding the
creation of new jobs, around 3,000 jobs were lost in the UK high street
branches alone. Mr Derek Wanless said the scale of job losses was likely to
remain close to this rate in the coming 18 months.
The dividend has been maintained at 6.125p out of earnings of 8p against 5p
a share.
Lex, Page 14; Observer, Page 13; Market report, Page 32
