FT  05 AUG 92 / Royal Bank of Scotland warns on bad debts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Bank of Scotland yesterday issued a gloomy trading statement, which in
part prompted a 12 per cent fall in its share price to 153p, writes Robert
Peston. The bank said it expected bad debt charges in the current financial
year to end-September, would exceed the previous year's record Pounds 351m.
The bank also announced plans to raise Dollars 200m (Pounds 104m) by an
issue of non-cumulative preference shares in the US. Merrill Lynch, US
securities firm will act as adviser.
Royal Bank said it did not expect any improvement in the 'recessionary
environment in the short term' and business conditions for the group would
probably 'remain difficult . . . through at least the remainder of calendar
1992'.
Royal Bank's share price was also depressed by an announcement of a claim
from Wallace Smith Trust, a company in liquidation, for reimbursement of
sums - with a total face value of Pounds 418m - allegedly transferred to the
wrong account. Royal Bank is contesting the claim.
