<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Elizabeth R attracted almost 18m viewers when first screened earlier this
year. With the Royal Family scarcely off the front pages since there should
be another bumper audience for this wry look at the business of Queenship.
The scenes of the happy home life at Balmoral will be intently scrutinised.
(ITV 8.00).
Death and the Compass, in BBC2's ScreenPlay slot at 9.30, is an adaptation
of a short story by Jorge Luis Borges. It is set, of course, in a Latin
American military dictatorship and stars Peter Boyle as the oddball
investigator of a series of murders.
Anthony Holden is a journalist who became a professional poker player good
enough to win through to the World Championships in Las Vegas and on BBC2 at
11.15 he takes us to the event which attracts the best players as well as
the bizarre characters who devote their lives to this mesmerising contest.
Soul singer James Brown always receives laudatory television coverage,
perhaps because of his age, (well into his sixties), perhaps because his
performance is much copied by younger black artists. Expect the same old
footage of his stage show, gold cape and all (Channel 4, 11.05).
</TEXT>
