<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / Strangeways tender open to private sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BIDS to manage the re-built Strangeways Prison, Manchester, which was
damaged during Britain's most serious jail riots of modern times, are to be
invited from both the public and private sectors.
If ministers choose a private-sector bid Strangeways will become Britain's
first old-established prison to be run by the private sector.
Strangeways is undergoing extensive refurbishment after damage caused by the
rioting two years ago, and bids for its management will be invited in the
autumn. Securicor, the security services group, said yesterday that it was
likely to be among those interested in bidding.
Ministers stressed yesterday, however, that the decision to involve the
private sector did not mean they had excluded the possibility of the public
prisons department making the winning bid.
Mr Peter Lloyd, minister responsible for prisons, spoke on BBC Radio
yesterday of the public service's 'huge reserves of skill, expertise and
dedication' but said these qualities had not been brought together in the
running of the prison service as effectively as the government would like.
Britain's first privately managed prison, the Wolds remand establishment on
Humberside, opened earlier this year. Blakenhurst in Hereford and Worcester,
another new development, will open under private management later this year
and will be the first to take convicted prisoners.
Ministers are anxious to modernise prison management and challenge the power
of the Prison Officers' Association. They see the introduction of
private-sector man-agement as a means of doing both.
The government believes that, provided the state sets and monitors
standards, there are no ethical objections to private prisons. Penal-reform
groups, however, say that profit considerations should not be involved in
depriving people of their liberty.
Mr Brian Caton, vice-chairman of the Prison Officers' Association, said he
feared that the decision to invite private-sector bids to manage Strangeways
would be repeated at other types of prison. 'We will not stand by and watch
an immoral practice continue without some kind of action,' he said.
Publication today of a severely critical report following the death of a
patient at Ashworth high security hospital, Merseyside, is expected to lead
to a government review of high-security hospitals.
Even before publication of the report of an inquiry led by Sir Louis
Blom-Cooper, chairman of the Mental Health Act Commission, mental health
organisations have started calling for the closure of Ashworth and the other
large high-security special hospitals at Broadmoor, Berkshire and Rampton,
Nottinghamshire.
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, said yesterday that 'all the
indications point to a scandal of staggering proportions' involving
rottenness and cruelty. The government had to respond to the report with
immediate action.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
