FT  05 AUG 92 / High Court action starts over pension funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH COURT proceedings have been started by members of two pension funds
controlled by the Nottingham-based Melton Medes, the mini-conglomerate run
by Mr Nathu Ram Puri.
The court action has been launched by the Graphical Paper and Media Union in
an attempt to obtain further information about the investment of scheme
assets and to appoint a judicial or independent trustee. It has been taken
on behalf of a number of beneficiaries of Robert Fletcher (Greenfield) and
Robert Fletcher (Stoneclough) Pension Funds against Melton Medes Pension
Trustees and MM Fund Management, the funds' trustees.
The funds relate to two Lancashire factories that were bought by Melton
Medes from the Imperial Group in 1986. A preliminary High Court hearing in
July placed assets, other than property, that had been controlled by the
trustees into the hands of Philips &amp; Drew, the professional fund manager
that was already handling part of the fund investments.
Undertakings were obtained from the trustees that they would not permit the
removal of the fund manager or intervene in the manager's investment
functions. The application for the appointment of an independent trustee is
to be heard in October.
The court action has arisen after a campaign by Mr Victor Edwards, a foreman
at Greenfield Mill, to enlist union financial support for a legal battle.
Last night Mr Puri said in a prepared statement: 'The trustees resolutely
deny any suggestion of financial or other impropriety in the management of
Robert Fletcher (Greenfield) and Robert Fletcher (Stoneclough) pension
funds.
'The interests of the members of the funds have always been, and remain, of
paramount importance to the trustees. We would add that the majority of the
assets of the funds have always been under independent financial fund
management. The remainder, except property, were placed under the management
of the same managers before there was any intimation of these proceedings.
'They were not placed with them because of these proceedings. The trustees
are not doing anything different today than they were doing before the
action.'
</TEXT>
