<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / TUC plans to change priorities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR trade unionists are proposing that the Trades Union Congress
concentrate on just six priorities - a third of the current total - in a
move they will present as a radical rethink of the TUC's role.
The proposals, made in a confidential document approved by the TUC's ruling
general council, have been formulated as a growing number of affiliated
unions are questioning the organisation's effectiveness following a fourth
consecutive Conservative general election victory.
The AEEU engineering and electrical union has called for a 'radical
reassessment' of the TUC in a motion submitted for the annual congress in
September. The TGWU general workers is also calling for a refocusing of the
organisation's role. Some union leaders have also questioned the TUC's
leadership.
The TUC document, due to be submitted to the September congress, follows a
20 per cent reduction in staff, implemented to avert financial deficits. It
acknowledges that a 'more sharply focused programme of work' is needed.
The TUC's priority tasks will be a campaign for full employment, promotion
of an employee's charter, lobbying on trade union legislation, Europe,
developing services on education, health and safety and equal rights and
'planning the inter-union future'.
On the last area, the general council is suggesting that a voluntary code be
reached between unions following the expected legislation to undermine
Bridlington rules covering membership poaching.
Although the document does not go into details on such a code, it is likely
that the TUC will propose that unions do not actively recruit each other's
members, even though the legislation would make it virtually impossible for
the congress to forbid poaching.
Current TUC policy is to concentrate on 17 priority areas. Those include the
development of free trade unions in central and eastern Europe, 'quality in
public services', joint action on training and union recruitment. The
document says the reduction cut in priorities provides a basis for
allocating the TUC's more limited resources and for a concentrated public
relations effort around proposed campaigns.
</TEXT>
