<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / Call for more inner-city land sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Redwood, the inner cities minister, is pressing urban development
corporations to step up sales of land for low-cost housing or for other uses
to supplement their grant incomes.
The government believes that some UDCs have held back on land sales in the
hope of capitalising on an improved market for commercial or industrial uses
when a recovery comes.
But Mr Redwood is urging the 11 English corporations to accelerate their
disposals of land, particularly to private home builders, in order to help
stimulate the construction industry and to increase the supply of affordable
homes.
With land values depressed, he believes that there is now a good opportunity
for developers to produce highly competitive 'starter' flats at retail
prices of between Pounds 35,000 and Pounds 40,000.
'I am very keen to see UDCs sell land in the current market conditions to
developers who can make housing for sale available at low market prices,'
the minister said.
UDCs are currently preparing their annual plans and have registered Mr
Redwood's proposal. However they also point out that in the current
conditions the market for new properties is finite.
Mr Martin Eagland, the chief executive of Leeds' UDC, said that in his area
the recent authorisation of a 300-unit residential development, much of it
low cost, meant that most local-market demand was probably satisfied.
Of the 1,300 acres in the Leeds Development Corporation's area, it directly
held 90 acres of which only 20 per cent would be suitable for preliminary
study as potential residential development.
Mr Eagland added, however, that Mr Redwood's plan would be closely examined,
not least as the corporation's grant has been cut from Pounds 13.6m in
1991-92 to an estimated Pounds 4m in the coming year.
</TEXT>
