<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / Bank chief defends tax credit scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Christopher Tugendhat, chairman of Abbey National, yesterday stood by
his controversial proposals for a tax credit scheme to revive the housing
market.
He said that it was an 'open secret' that Whitehall was looking for ways to
solve the housing market recession.
Sir Christopher said that he was a bit taken aback that much of the media
had missed key characteristics of his proposals, including the Pounds 10,000
ceiling on the tax credit.
'It was an embryo idea rather than a fully worked up proposal. We hoped that
other lenders would contribute to that process as well.'
He remained reasonably confident that there would be a housing recovery,
even without a government initiative to revitalise the market.
'We do not believe in the disaster scenario. I don't doubt that the housing
market will revive. We can already see some encouraging features in it. But
there is a big difference between sooner and later as far as the economic
situation is concerned,' he said.
'The later it happens, the more pain there will be and the more jobs and
businesses there will be lost and also the greater the pressure the
government will come under.'
Sir Christopher said he was disappointed that some people had seen his
proposals as self-seeking. 'We at Abbey National do not need a plan of this
sort ourselves. The outlook from Abbey National is probably a bit better
than it is from many other vantage points.'
He also rejected claims that Abbey National had underestimated the cost of
its proposals. He said the bank had been very tentative about potential
costs because there were several complex and uncertain factors involved.
</TEXT>
