<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / Italy passes tough Mafia law: Decree to strengthen hand of
authorities wins cross-party support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S new government last night won approval in the lower house of
parliament for a tough new anti-Mafia decree.
Put forward after the recent murders of Mr Giovanni Falcone and Mr Paolo
Borsellino, two prominent judges in Sicily leading the fight against the
Mafia, the new ruling will strengthen the hand of police and magistrates
tackling criminal organisations.
The lower house also passed an amendment which means politicians caught
buying votes from gangsters could face up to six years in prison.
The government, led by Mr Giuliano Amato, has been faced with a public
outcry since the two assassinations. Its immediate reactions after last
month's murder of Mr Borsellino included sending 7,000 troops to Sicily to
help local police and carabinieri.
The government decided not to turn the vote on the new decree - which had
already been approved in the Senate, the upper house - into an issue of
confidence, following signs of broad cross-party support.
It did however agree to drop a clause which would have given police greater
powers to detain suspects without charge following criticism from the main
opposition Democratic Party of the Left (PDS).
The decree will also lay to rest the High Commission for the Fight against
the Mafia, which was set up in the early 1980s but which has proved
ineffective in tackling organised crime.
The organisation would have become partly redundant next year, when Italy's
new anti-Mafia DIA, modelled on America's FBI, comes into operation. Italy's
financial markets rebounded for the second day running yesterday after
Monday night's surprise cut in interest rates by the Bank of Italy and last
week's agreement on ending the scala mobile wage indexing system.
The half-point reduction in the official discount rate to 13.25 per cent and
in the rate for fixed-term advances to commercial banks to 14.75 per cent
contributed to a slight decline in the lira. The Italian currency was fixed
at 755.83 against the D-Mark, compared with 754.95 on Monday.
Shares on the Milan stock exchange rose for the second consecutive day, with
prices rising by over 2 per cent and the Comit equity index closing up 7.71
points at 424.35. However, brokers warned that the rise came against a
background of very thin trading.
