<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / Freeze on European fighter contracts agreed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A THREE-MONTH freeze in new contracts in the development of the
controversial European Fighter Aircraft was agreed yesterday by defence
ministers from Germany, Britain, Italy and Spain.
The time will be used to undertake studies to find drastic cost reductions
in the Pounds 20bn project and to redefine the aircraft's military role.
The ministers, meeting in Madrid, stopped short of suggesting that the EFA
would not be built. But Spain and Germany - which triggered a crisis in the
consortium earlier this summer by declaring it would not join the production
phase of the aircraft - left little doubt that the original project is on
the verge of being abandoned.
'The EFA is dead,' Mr Volker Ruhe, the German defence minister, said
yesterday. His Spanish counterpart, Mr Julian Garcia Vargas, said: 'Our
current economic situation will not permit us to go into production of the
EFA as it stands.'
Only Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the UK defence secretary, tried to sound an
enthusiastic note by insisting that Germany had agreed to continue the
development phase of the EFA. But Mr Ruhe, who has never threatened
otherwise, noted that for the first time 'London has shown a readiness to
discuss a reduction of the military and strategic requirements of the
aircraft'.
In a clear reference to Mr Ruhe's calls for a cheaper and lighter EFA, Mr
Rifkind said: 'We very much hope that the decisions eventually taken will be
informed rather than those based on simple assertions without any supporting
hard evidence . . . It is unlikely that any project which does not take
advantage of the huge expense already undertaken on development will end up
being less expensive than the EFA.'
He said a 30 per cent cut in unit costs being sought by Spain was a broad
target and 'we are happy they should look at that'. The decision to freeze
new development contracts was purely symbolic, he said. There were, as far
as he knew, no new ones pending.
Mr Garca Vargas said the ministers had agreed that no new contracts would be
awarded between now and the end of October.
During this time the air forces of the four countries would study
alternative military requirements.
Mr Garca Vargas said the ministers would meet again in November to decide
whether to proceed with the EFA, to build a lighter, cheaper version or to
begin work - possibly with other partners and investors including Saudi
Arabia - on a new aircraft. He warned that the 'pause' would inevitably mean
a delay in the production of whatever aircraft it was decided to build.
Spain would insist on a twin-engined aircraft, but he said the studies would
look at changes in all aspects of the EFA, including the airframe, which
Britain has been keen to protect.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
