<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / UK banks face Pounds 490m suit: Liquidators allege payments
to Wallace Smith Trust misdirected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK, ROBERT PESTON, RICHARD DONKIN and RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROYAL Bank of Scotland is being sued for up to Pounds 418m and National
Westminster for more than Pounds 71m by the liquidators of a small banking
group which was closed down last year by the Bank of England after
involvement in alleged fraud.
Neither bank has made provisions against any losses which may result from
the legal action.
The Pounds 418m claim against Royal Bank of Scotland is roughly equivalent
to its full-year profits before provisions. Its shares fell 21p yesterday to
153p, while those of NatWest dropped 4p to 320p.
The damage claims stem from allegations that substantial payments that
should have been deposited with the Wallace Smith Trust Company were made by
the banks to another company, Wallace Smith Holdings.
Wallace Smith Trust Company's liquidator, Mr Tim Hayward, head of corporate
recovery at KPMG Peat Marwick, claims the payments were non-transferable and
should not have been rerouted. The banks say the rerouting was properly
authorised.
Mr Hayward has issued a writ against Royal Bank of Scotland. NatWest has not
yet received a writ though it expects to receive one.
Wallace Smith Trust was a banking and finance group closed down by the Bank
of England in May last year. Wallace Smith Holdings was a general financial
services company.
Mr Wallace Duncan Smith, a director of Wallace Smith Trust, has been charged
with fraud exceeding Dollars 50m. Mr Smith, 58, has a wealthy, though
private lifestyle, with an address in Chelsea and property in the Bahamas.
Born in western Canada, he is described as a family man.
He is well known among the Bruges Group of anti-European federalists and is
known to have paid the rent on the Bruges Group's one-room office in Jermyn
Street for nearly two years.
Mr Smith was arrested in April last year and charged with fraudulent
trading. His case was transferred from City of London magistrates court 12
months later, by which time he faced 15 charges. His trial has been fixed
for February 1 at Knightsbridge Crown Court.
Two charges of fraudulent trading allege that between January 1980 and April
1991 he was knowingly a party to carrying on the business of Wallace Smith
Trust with intent to defraud its creditors.
Royal Bank of Scotland said its writ claimed 'damages in conversion' for 39
payments made between August 1989 and January 1991. Eleven payments
originated from Deutsche Genossenschaftsbank and 28 from Bank of New York.
The bank said yesterday: 'We deny liability and are going to vigorously
contend these allegations.'
National Westminster said in a note to its interim accounts, released
yesterday, that it had been advised of a claim 'arising out of the conduct
of (a former) customer's account'.
Profile, Page 5
Bad debt warning, Page 15
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
