<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 92 / Building company shares fall further
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARE PRICES of hard-pressed construction and building material companies
fell further yesterday as pressure mounted on the government to revive
Britain's flagging housing market.
Mr Donald Kirkham, chief executive of Woolwich, Britain's fourth largest
building society, appealed to the government to allow mortgage tax relief on
loans of up to Pounds 60,000 for the first 12 months after a house purchase.
He also wants the threshold for stamp duty on house purchases raised to
Pounds 60,000.
He said householders were feeling less wealthy every month as house prices
and consumer confidence dwindled. People were saving more and spending less,
causing higher unemployment.
The call for urgent action to end the recession in the housing market and
pave the way for a general recovery came a day after Abbey National urged
the government to offer tax relief of up to Pounds 10,000 to people selling
their home at a loss. Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said he would
consider the idea but is expected to reject it.
Share prices of construction companies dropped yesterday following
publication of figures showing a further sharp fall in housebuilding in the
three months after the election in April. The FT-Actuaries index of leading
construction shares fell by 2.6 per cent to 609.68. The FT-A building
materials index fell 3.2 per cent to 756.43.
Housebuilders started work on 8 per cent fewer homes in the second quarter
than during the previous three months, according to the Environment
Department. The total number of starts of 38,900 was the lowest quarterly
figure since the final three months of 1990 when the housing market was at a
very low ebb.
Publication of the figures came as Lord Alexander, chairman of National
Westminster Bank, urged a three-point plan to spur recovery. He wants to
boost the housing market by doubling the ceiling on mortgage interest tax
relief to about Pounds 60,000, although he wants all mortgage tax relief
abolished in 10 years.
The bank also favours greater government spending on transport and
infrastructure and is promoting the granting of accelerated tax allowances
on capital investment by companies.
General Accident, the insurance group, revealed that its property services
division is offering insurance against falling house prices for anxious
purchasers of new homes.
House starts fall, Page 5
Editorial Comment, Page 12
Lex, Page 14
NatWest results, Page 15
</TEXT>
